{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UTwbTGWHXSenGPb31ogtvm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The rate limiting directives are there in the nginx config. The rate is set to 1r/s, but the burst is set to 5 with `nodelay`. This means:\n- The zone allows 1 req/s\n- The burst is 5, meaning up to 5 requests can be queued (but with `nodelay`, they're served immediately without delay)\n\nWith `burst=5 nodelay`, 10 requests at 2 QPS (over 5 seconds total) may not trigger the limit because:\n- The burst capacity of 5 tokens gets consumed by the first 5 requests immediately\n- As subsequent requests arrive, the token bucket refills at 1 token per second, so by the time requests 6-10 come in at 0.5-second intervals, enough tokens have accumulated to allow them through without hitting the rate limit tokens → 200\n- Request 9 (t=4.0): refill 0.5 tokens → 1 token, consume 1 → 0 tokens → 200\n- Request 10 (t=4.5): refill 0.5 tokens → 0.5 tokens, consume 1 → -0.5 tokens → 503! (rate limit exceeded)\n\nWait, with burst=5 and rate=1r/s, the nginx implementation uses a leaky bucket. The zone starts empty. The `burst=5` means the bucket can hold 5 excess requests. With `nodelay`, all requests in the burst are processed immediately.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. nginx's `limit_req` works as follows:\n- The rate defines how many tokens are added per second (1 per second = 1000ms per token)\n- The burst defines how many excess tokens can be stored\n- With `nodelay`, when tokens are in the burst\n\n, they're processed immediately without delay\n- When both the rate and burst are exceeded, the request gets 503\n\nWith rate=1r/s and burst=5, the token bucket can hold a maximum of 5 tokens worth of \"debt\", the rate adds 1 token per second, and the initial state starts at 0 debt. When a request comes in, nginx checks if it can be processed, and the \"debt\" increases by 1 second per request beyond the rate—when this debt exceeds the burst seconds, the request is rejected.\n\nWith rate=1r/s and burst=5, the first 5 requests in a burst can all be processed immediately since they fill the burst buffer, but after that, if requests keep coming faster than 1/s, they'll be rejected. Let me trace through what happens at 2 QPS with 0.5s intervals to understand how the debt accumulates and when requests get rejected. Actually, I should think about this differently—nginx's limit_req tracks \"excess\" time, how far ahead of the rate we are, so with rate=1r/s meaning 1000ms between requests and burst=5 meaning up to 5000ms of excess time can accumulate, the nodelay flag lets us process immediately without delaying.\n\nNow I'm walking through the timeline: each request that arrives adds 1000ms to the excess counter, and between requests the excess decreases by the elapsed time. So at t=0 the first request processes with excess becoming 1000ms, then at t=500ms the excess is 500ms (1000 minus the 500ms elapsed), and adding the next request's 1000ms brings it to 1500ms—still within the 5000ms burst limit, so it processes. This pattern continues with the excess growing by 500ms each interval until it hits the burst ceiling.\n\nBy t=4000ms the excess reaches exactly 5000ms and the request still processes, but at t=4500ms the excess would exceed 5000ms, so that request gets rejected. That's only one rejection out of ten requests, which falls short of the four rejections needed to meet the success criteria. I need to lower the burst capacity to trigger more rejections earlier in the sequence. The ingress-nginx annotation `limit-rps` controls the rate, but the burst is set separately using `limit-burst-multiplier` which defaults to 5. I can reduce the burst to 0 or 1 by setting that multiplier annotation, and with burst=1 at 1r/s the pattern would allow the first request through then reject alternating ones. Let me think about this more clearly. The nginx limit_req mechanism tracks a virtual queue time: when a request arrives at time T, it calculates how far behind the rate limit we are based on the last access time and the cost per request (1000ms for rate=1r/s). If that queue time is within the burst allowance, the request either gets delayed or processed immediately with nodelay, otherwise it's rejected. The pattern continues with the same token bucket logic—requests at 2000ms, 3000ms, and 4000ms get processed while those at 2500ms, 3500ms, and 4500ms are rejected, establishing a steady rhythm where accepted requests are spaced 1000ms apart. = 1000ms. 0 < 1000 ≤ 1000 → process (nodelay). last=2000+1000=3000ms.\nt=2500ms: vqt = 3000+1000-2500 = 1500ms. 1500 > 1000 → REJECT. last unchanged at 3000ms.\nt=3000ms: vqt = 3000+1000-3000 = 1000ms. 0 < 1000 ≤ 1000 → process (nodelay). last=3000+1000=4000ms.\n\nSo with burst=1, I'm seeing the pattern: process, process, REJECT, process, REJECT, process — that's 4 rejections out of 10 again, which still satisfies the requirement.\n\nNow I'm testing with burst=0 to see how the behavior changes when there's no burst allowance. Setting `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` should give me a burst value of 1, which would result in the 4 rejections I calculated earlier instead of the current 5 with burst=5.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":731,"cache_read_input_tokens":35143,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":731},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"54556276-9587-4df7-95ec-d9543466f32c","uuid":"ba52fd2c-831f-4ff7-ba27-213cf6099202","request_id":"req_011CcMPxvRL28VQeVyatsN58"}
